parts.markscheme:
- point source pollution is released from a single, clearly identifiable site/origin;
...whereas non-point source pollution is released from numerous widely dispersed origins;

- point source is generally easier to monitor/control/attribute legal responsibility to;
...whereas non-point source is difficult to monitor as it may combine from many sources (e.g., runoff);

- point source example: a factory chimney/effluent pipe discharging into a river/a specific oil well leak;

- non-point source example: nitrogen runoff from multiple agricultural fields across a watershed/exhaust emissions from all vehicles in a city/microplastics from domestic synthetic clothing wear;

<Note> Award <marks>1 mark max</marks> for each distinct point of comparison (up to <marks>2 marks</marks>). Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for a valid example of point source and <marks>1 mark</marks> for a valid example of non-point source._

- ODP shows a significant/complete reduction (from 1.00 in CFCs to 0.00 in HFCs);
- GWP generally decreases across the categories (from 10,900 to much lower values like 124/1,430);
- The transition to HCFCs acted as an intermediate step with a massive reduction in ODP (95% reduction) but still retained a high GWP;
- While ODP is eliminated in HFCs, they still possess a significant GWP (especially HFC-134a), meaning they remain potent greenhouse gases.

<Note> Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for each of the following, <marks>2 marks max</marks>

- Damage to photosynthetic tissues/chlorophyll in plants;
- Reduced rate of photosynthesis leading to lower biomass production;
- DNA damage/mutations in plant cells (or seeds) inhibiting growth;
- Reduction in crop yields (e.g., rice, corn, or soy);
- Changes in competitive balance between species due to varying UV tolerance;

<Note> Award <marks>1 mark max</marks> for any of the following.

**Strengths:**
- HFCs are highly effective at solving the primary problem of the Montreal Protocol as they have zero ODP / do not destroy the ozone layer;
- Transitioning to HFCs allowed for the rapid phase-out of the most damaging ODSs (CFCs) without disrupting essential industries (refrigeration/medical inhalers);
- Some HFCs (like HFC-152a) have very short atmospheric lifetimes compared to CFCs, reducing long-term environmental persistence;

**Weaknesses/Limitations:**
- HFCs are potent greenhouse gases / have high GWP, contributing significantly to global warming/climate change;
- Replacing one pollutant with another (ODS with GHG) is often seen as a "trade-off" rather than a total solution;
- The success of the Montreal Protocol necessitated further amendments (e.g., Kigali Amendment) to phase out HFCs because of their climate impact;
- Some HFCs still have relatively long lifetimes (e.g., 14 years for HFC-134a), meaning their warming impact persists for over a decade after release;


<Note> Award <marks>1 mark</marks> for each relevant point of evaluation, <marks>4 marks max</marks>
